  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-burns-chunk-0013',
      title: 'Burns - Injuries and Poisoning - MSD Manual Consumer Version #13 Generally, a doctor’s examination and treatment',
      summary: 'Generally, a doctor’s examination and treatment are recommended if a tetanus vaccination is needed.',
      steps: [
        'Likewise, a doctor should examine a burn if it has any of the following characteristics: Is larger than the size of the person’s open hand Contains blisters Darkens or breaks the skin Involves the face, hand, foot, genitals, or skinfolds Is not completely clean Causes pain that is not relieved by acetaminophen Causes pain that is not relieved by acetaminophen Causes pain that does not decrease within 1 day after the burn was sustained Deep minor burns As with more superficial burns, deep minor burns are usually treated with antibiotic salves.',
        'Sometimes doctors do not use antibiotic salves but instead apply special sterile dressings that can be left in place for several days to a week.',
        'Some of these dressings contain silver, which helps kill bacteria.',
        'Other dressings are slightly porous—just enough to allow fluid to drain from the burn but not enough to let bacteria through.',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
      escalation: '原始来源：MSD Manual / Burns - Injuries and Poisoning - MSD Manual Consumer Version',
