      title: 'Emergency First Aid Priorities - Injuries and Poisoning - MSD Manual Consumer Version #3 If only one rescuer is available, wait to call f',
      summary: 'If only one rescuer is available, wait to call for help until after starting emergency care.',
      steps: [
        'After calling 911 or the local emergency service, rescuers, when necessary, can also give people the following rescue medications: Epinephrine in a premeasured, single-dose, intramuscular injection device (for example, EpiPen) for life-threatening allergic reactions ( Epinephrine in a premeasured, single-dose, intramuscular injection device (for example, EpiPen) for life-threatening allergic reactions ( anaphylaxis ), such as after a bee sting or eating a food a person is allergic to Naloxone , in the nose or by intramuscular injection, if a person stops or nearly stops breathing after an Naloxone, in the nose or by intramuscular injection, if a person stops or nearly stops breathing after an opioid drug overdose (for example, heroin, oxycodone [including Oxycontin], fentanyl ) (for example, heroin, oxycodone [including Oxycontin], fentanyl) If many people are injured, the most seriously injured person should be treated first.',
