  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0020-chunk-0001',
      title: 'Clotting Disorders Caused by Circulating Anticoagulants - Blood Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #1 Clotting Disorders Caused by Circulating Anticoa',
      summary: 'Clotting Disorders Caused by Circulating Anticoagulants By Michael B.',
      steps: [
        'Streiff , MD , Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine Reviewed/Revised Jul 2025 | Modified Feb 2026 v11648597 Multimedia | Sometimes a malfunction of the body\'s immune system causes it to make antibodies that attack the person\'s own tissues (autoantibodies) instead of attacking foreign or dangerous substances.',
        'Such disorders are called autoimmune disorders .',
        'Circulating anticoagulants are usually autoantibodies that develop spontaneously (on their own and without a known cause) and decrease the activity of a specific clotting factor (a protein that helps the blood clot) and, therefore, cause excessive bleeding (see also Overview of Blood Clotting Disorders ).',
        'For example, the immune system may produce an autoantibody against clotting factor VIII or factor V.',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
      escalation: '原始来源：MSD Manual / Clotting Disorders Caused by Circulating Anticoagulants - Blood Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version',
