  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0020-chunk-0002',
      title: 'Clotting Disorders Caused by Circulating Anticoagulants - Blood Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #2 However, some people with certain types of circu',
      summary: 'However, some people with certain types of circulating anticoagulants develop blood clots within an artery or vein instead of excessive bleeding.',
      steps: [
        'Such blood clots may cut off blood flow, causing redness and swelling as well as damage to the tissue supplied by the blood vessel.',
        'Circulating anticoagulants are suspected in people with excessive bleeding combined with abnormal coagulation test results.',
        'Treatment may include medications to suppress autoantibody production in people without hemophilia.',
        'Factor VIII and factor IX inhibitors Antibodies to factor VIII develop in about 30% of people with severe hemophilia A .',
      ],
