  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0035-chunk-0001',
      title: 'Hemosiderosis - Blood Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #1 Hemosiderosis By James Peter Adam Hamilton , MD',
      summary: 'Hemosiderosis By James Peter Adam Hamilton , MD , Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine Reviewed/Revised Modified Jan 2025 v8486015 Hemosiderosis is a term used for excessive',
      steps: [
        '(See also Overview of Iron Overload .) The lungs, liver, spleen, bone marrow, and kidneys are often sites of hemosiderosis.',
        'Hemosiderosis can result from Direct bleeding into the tissues that is followed by breakdown of red blood cells and release of iron to the tissues Breakdown of red blood cells within the blood vessels, leading to release of iron into the blood followed by accumulation of iron inside the kidneys as the kidneys filter waste from the blood Organs may be, but are usually not, damaged by the iron deposits.',
        'The extent of the damage depends on how much iron is deposited in the organs.',
        'Some people have no damage at all, whereas others have some damage.',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
