  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0096-chunk-0002',
      title: 'Medial and Lateral Plantar Nerve Entrapment - Bone, Joint, and Muscle Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #2 Burning, numbness, and tingling, which often occ',
      summary: 'Burning, numbness, and tingling, which often occur when nerves are compressed, usually do not occur in medial and lateral plantar nerve entrapment.',
      steps: [
        'Diagnosis of Medial and Lateral Plantar Nerve Entrapment A doctor\'s examination Doctors base the diagnosis of medial and lateral plantar nerve entrapment on the person’s symptoms and the results of an examination.',
        'Treatment of Medial and Lateral Plantar Nerve Entrapment Splints, orthoses, and physical therapy Devices that keep the foot from moving (such as splints) and other devices placed in the shoe (orthoses) may help, as may physical therapy and application of extreme cold to the nerve ( cryotherapy ).',
        'If these treatments do not work, injection with an alcohol solution to deaden the nerve or surgery to free the nerve from compression may help relieve pain.',
        'Test your Knowledge Take a Quiz!',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
