  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0175-chunk-0002',
      title: 'Horner Syndrome - Brain, Spinal Cord, and Nerve Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #2 They exit the spinal cord in the chest, then go',
      summary: 'They exit the spinal cord in the chest, then go back up the neck beside the carotid artery, through the skull, and into the eye.',
      steps: [
        'If these nerve fibers are disrupted anywhere along their pathway, Horner syndrome results.',
        'Horner syndrome may occur on its own or be caused by another disorder.',
        'For example, it can be caused by disorders of the head, brain, neck, chest, or spinal cord, such as the following: Lung cancer Other tumors Swollen lymph glands in the neck (cervical adenopathy) Dissection of the aorta or carotid artery (a tear in the lining of the artery\'s wall) A thoracic aortic aneurysm (a bulge in the aorta\'s wall) Injuries Horner syndrome may be present at birth (congenital).',
        'Symptoms of Horner Syndrome Horner syndrome affects the eye on the same side as the disrupted nerve fibers.',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
      escalation: '原始来源：MSD Manual / Horner Syndrome - Brain, Spinal Cord, and Nerve Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version',
