  KnowledgeEntry(
      id: 'merck-home-topic-0186-chunk-0002',
      title: 'Aphasia - Brain, Spinal Cord, and Nerve Disorders - MSD Manual Consumer Version #2 Thus, in most people, language function is contr',
      summary: 'Thus, in most people, language function is controlled by the following areas of the brain: Part of the left frontal lobe called Broca area Part of the left temporal lobe called Wer',
      steps: [
        'Usually, writing and speech are affected similarly.',
        'Hidden Disability: Aphasia video Causes of Aphasia Aphasia usually results from disorders that do not cause progressive damage, such as the following: A stroke A head injury A brain infection ( encephalitis ) In such cases, aphasia does not continue to worsen over time.',
        'If aphasia results from a progressive disorder (such as an enlarging brain tumor), it can progressively worsen.',
        'As the tumor gets bigger, it may put more pressure on areas of the brain that control language function and further impair the ability to express or understand language.',
      ],
      contraindications: const <String>[],
